Date: Mon, 7 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Include signal.h for SYS_SECCOMP to fix enum redefinition conflict

Recent glibc defines SYS_SECCOMP as an enum value in bits/siginfo-consts.h
along with a self-referential macro alias. Without including signal.h first,
linux_seccomp.h defines SYS_SECCOMP=1 via its #ifndef guard, and then when
signal.h is included later in a translation unit the enum identifier
SYS_SECCOMP gets macro-expanded to 1, causing a syntax error.

Fix by including <signal.h> at the top of linux_seccomp.h so glibc's
definition takes precedence and the #ifndef guard suppresses our #define.
This matches the fix already landed in Firefox main.

Upstream-Status: Backport

--- a/security/sandbox/chromium/sandbox/linux/system_headers/linux_seccomp.h
+++ b/security/sandbox/chromium/sandbox/linux/system_headers/linux_seccomp.h
@@ -6,5 +6,6 @@
 #define SANDBOX_LINUX_SYSTEM_HEADERS_LINUX_SECCOMP_H_
 
+#include <signal.h> // for SYS_SECCOMP
 #include <stdint.h>
 #include <sys/ioctl.h>
 
